00:48:14,410 --> 00:48:17,121
- Not an exit.
- We don't want an exit.

701
00:48:17,287 --> 00:48:19,748
- No, that's true.
- This way.

702
00:48:19,915 --> 00:48:22,334
Yeah, this way. Let's go.

703
00:48:26,004 --> 00:48:27,297
Um...

704
00:48:27,464 --> 00:48:31,051
- Wait. This looks familiar, though.
- Listen!

705
00:48:35,180 --> 00:48:36,974
Shit!

706
00:48:39,017 --> 00:48:40,978
Let's not lose it, let's not lose it.

707
00:48:41,144 --> 00:48:43,271
Where the fuck is Ian?
He should be here.

708
00:48:43,438 --> 00:48:45,524
Tap! Tap! Tap! Tap!

709
00:48:46,441 --> 00:48:50,529
We've gotta get to it some way.
We've been onstage, right?

710
00:48:51,905 --> 00:48:55,367
We're in the group.
We're in the group that's playin' tonight.

711
00:48:55,534 --> 00:49:00,539
You go straight through this door here,
down the hall, turn right,

712
00:49:00,705 --> 00:49:04,501
and then there's a little jog,
about 30 feet. Jog to the left.

713
00:49:04,668 --> 00:49:08,129
- We don't have time for that.
- Go straight ahead,

714
00:49:08,296 --> 00:49:10,465
turn right at the next two corners.

715
00:49:10,632 --> 00:49:14,010
On the first door is a sign:
"authorised personnel only".

716
00:49:14,177 --> 00:49:16,763
- Open that door. That's the stage.
- You think so?

717
00:49:16,930 --> 00:49:19,599
You're authorised.
You're musicians, aren't ya?

718
00:49:19,766 --> 00:49:21,685
Thank you. Thank you very much.

719
00:49:21,851 --> 00:49:23,645
Rock'n'roll!

720
00:49:23,812 --> 00:49:24,813
Rock'n'roll!

721
00:49:24,979 --> 00:49:27,399
Let's get it! Let's get it!

722
00:49:27,565 --> 00:49:29,734
- This way?
- No, this way.

723
00:49:29,901 --> 00:49:31,945
Straight through. Rock'n'roll!

724
00:49:32,112 --> 00:49:35,156
Hello, Cleveland! Hello, Cleveland!

725
00:49:37,200 --> 00:49:40,745
- Fuck!
- You must've made a wrong turn.

726
00:49:41,162 --> 00:49:46,417
- We gotta go another way.
- Other way, other way. Other way!

727
00:49:47,001 --> 00:49:51,589
I hate to keep harping on, but the notion
of a black album has cursed us.

728
00:49:51,756 --> 00:49:55,718
We're getting substantial reports
of airplay. Don't worry about that.

729
00:49:55,885 --> 00:50:00,598
But... it might have been better if the, uh...
album had been mixed right.

730
00:50:00,765 --> 00:50:04,102
Well, no use crying over that,
but of course that's true.

731
00:50:04,268 --> 00:50:06,729
Well, it was mixed all wrong, wasn't it?

732
00:50:06,896 --> 00:50:09,190
It was mixed wrong? Were you there?

733
00:50:09,357 --> 00:50:14,153
- But she's heard the record.
- So your judgment is it was mixed wrong.

734
00:50:14,320 --> 00:50:17,865
- You couldn't hear the lyrics.
- You don't agree?

735
00:50:18,032 --> 00:50:20,701
- No, I do not agree.
- Well, I think maybe...

736
00:50:20,827 --> 00:50:24,539
- It's interesting she's bringing it up.
- She'd like to hear the vocals.

737
00:50:24,705 --> 00:50:28,626
It's like me saying you're using
the wrong conditioner for your hair.

738
00:50:28,793 --> 00:50:31,295
It looks sort of frizzy.

739
00:50:31,462 --> 00:50:35,633
- You don't do 'eavy metal in Dubly.
- In what? In what?

740
00:50:38,260 --> 00:50:42,431
- In Dubly. You can't...
- She means Dolby, all right?

741
00:50:42,598 --> 00:50:44,141
You know what she means.

742
00:50:44,809 --> 00:50:47,353
You shan't recover from this one.

743
00:50:47,520 --> 00:50:52,691
Can I have the floor for just one moment?
I've got something I'd like to show you.

744
00:50:53,651 --> 00:50:56,403
Jeanine's been working
on these very hard.

745
00:50:56,570 --> 00:50:59,990
- These are a new direction...
- A new presentation.

746
00:51:00,157 --> 00:51:03,535
The stage look of the band,
based on the signs of the zodiac.

747
00:51:03,702 --> 00:51:05,246
We need a new presentation.

748
00:51:05,412 --> 00:51:11,418
This is a look for Viv. He's a Libra.
There's the sort of Yin/Yang sort of look.

749
00:51:11,585 --> 00:51:14,546
This is Nigel. He's Capricorn.

750
00:51:15,005 --> 00:51:17,091
- Sort of a goat look.
- With a beard.

751
00:51:17,257 --> 00:51:19,426
- Is this a joke?
- This...

752
00:51:19,593 --> 00:51:23,180
- Excuse me. Is this a joke?
- Just bear with us for one moment.

753
00:51:23,347 --> 00:51:26,141
This... I love this.
I wish I were Cancer.

754
00:51:26,308 --> 00:51:28,977
- That's attractive.
- This is your crab face.

755
00:51:29,144 --> 00:51:30,938
Give it a chance.

756
00:51:31,104 --> 00:51:34,650
- And this is...
- David, wait, please. Wait a minute.

757
00:51:34,816 --> 00:51:40,322
Have you any idea what it will cost
to dress up the band as animals?

758
00:51:40,489 --> 00:51:43,492
- Oh, it don't cost nothin'.
- They're not animals...

759
00:51:43,659 --> 00:51:46,995
It's a way to fight the drabs.
We've got the drabs.

760
00:51:47,162 --> 00:51:51,458
That's true. I think mine would look better
in Dubly. If it was done in Dubly...

761
00:51:51,625 --> 00:51:53,293
Shut up!

762
00:51:53,460 --> 00:51:57,130
- If you're not open-minded enough...
- David...

763
00:51:57,297 --> 00:51:59,716
There are solutions to our problems.

764
00:51:59,883 --> 00:52:03,220
- I think we know what they are.
- I've yet to hear them.

765
00:52:03,386 --> 00:52:06,473
We can take a rational approach.
We can say...

766
00:52:06,640 --> 00:52:10,560
- May I make a suggestion?
- Oh, let's hear your suggestion.

767
00:52:10,727 --> 00:52:13,230
Stonehenge. Stonehenge.

768
00:52:13,396 --> 00:52:15,482
Best production value we've ever had.

769
00:52:15,649 --> 00:52:19,486
But we haven't got the equipment.
We haven't got Stonehenge.

770
00:52:19,653 --> 00:52:21,529
Please, please. Just a moment.

771
00:52:21,696 --> 00:52:25,075
- Musically, we all know it.
- It's not a bad idea.

772
00:52:25,241 --> 00:52:29,829
No problems musically.
We go right onstage and it's quite simple.

773
00:52:29,996 --> 00:52:32,082
Ian can take care of this.

774
00:52:32,749 --> 00:52:36,086
But we don't have
that piece of scenery any more.

775
00:52:36,252 --> 00:52:38,797
I know! So we build a new one.

776
00:52:39,798 --> 00:52:43,676
- And this is it.
- Consider it done.

777
00:52:43,843 --> 00:52:47,764
You're just gonna take care of it like that?
Using that as the plans?

778
00:52:47,931 --> 00:52:50,141
- Let's try.
- If you can do it, I'll do the number.

779
00:52:50,934 --> 00:52:53,478
Do you feel that,
in collaboration with David,

780
00:52:53,645 --> 00:52:58,066
that you are afforded the opportunity
to express yourself musically

781
00:52:58,232 --> 00:53:01,736
- The way you would like to?
- Well, I think I do, in my solos.

782
00:53:01,903 --> 00:53:03,488
My solos are my trademark.

783
00:53:50,785 --> 00:53:53,120
Perfect. It's the right proportions.

784
00:53:53,204 --> 00:53:55,206
- It'll be this colour, right?
- Yeah.

785
00:53:55,372 --> 00:53:58,751
That's just terrific.
It almost looks like the real thing.

786
00:53:58,918 --> 00:54:00,336
- You got it.
- Yeah.

787
00:54:00,503 --> 00:54:02,338
When we get the actual set,

788
00:54:02,505 --> 00:54:06,425
it'll follow exactly these specifications?
Even these contours?

789
00:54:06,592 --> 00:54:10,221
Um... I don't understand you.
The actual piece?

790
00:54:10,387 --> 00:54:15,017
- When you build the actual piece...
- But this is what you asked for, isn't it?

791
00:54:15,184 --> 00:54:17,770
- What?
- Well, this is the piece.

792
00:54:17,936 --> 00:54:20,022
- This is the piece?
- Yes.

793
00:54:20,189 --> 00:54:25,069
Are you telling me that this is it?
This is scenery?

794
00:54:25,235 --> 00:54:27,237
Have you ever been to Stonehenge?

795
00:54:27,404 --> 00:54:31,450
The triptychs are 20 feet high!
You can stand four men up 'em!

796
00:54:31,617 --> 00:54:35,204
Ian, I was asked to build it 18 inches high!

797
00:54:35,370 --> 00:54:38,248
Look. This is what I was asked to build.

798
00:54:38,415 --> 00:54:42,085
18 inches. Right here.
It's specified, 18 inches.

799
00:54:42,252 --> 00:54:45,714
- I was given this napkin.
- Forget this! Fuck the napkin!

800
00:54:50,761 --> 00:54:53,055
In ancient times,

801
00:54:54,806 --> 00:54:58,894
hundreds of years
before the dawn of history,

802
00:55:00,395 --> 00:55:03,440
lived an ancient race of people.

803
00:55:05,901 --> 00:55:07,277
The Druids.

804
00:55:17,329 --> 00:55:19,998
No one knows who they were

805
00:55:21,958 --> 00:55:23,919
or

806
00:55:24,085 --> 00:55:26,504
what they were doing.

807
00:55:27,756 --> 00:55:30,425
But their legacy remains.

808
00:55:31,509 --> 00:55:33,511
Hewn

809
00:55:34,387 --> 00:55:36,931
into the living rock

810
00:55:37,098 --> 00:55:39,309
of Stonehenge.

811
00:55:51,237 --> 00:55:54,324
Stonehenge-where the demons dwell

812
00:55:54,491 --> 00:55:58,244
Where the banshees live
and they do live well

813
00:55:58,411 --> 00:56:01,748
Stonehenge-where a man is a man

814
00:56:01,915 --> 00:56:05,376
And the children dance
to the pipes of Pan

815
00:56:10,381 --> 00:56:12,467
And you, my love

816
00:56:12,633 --> 00:56:14,844
Won't you take my hand

817
00:56:16,763 --> 00:56:18,765
We'll go back in time

818
00:56:19,932 --> 00:56:22,351
To that mystic land

819
00:56:24,604 --> 00:56:27,023
Where the dewdrops cry

820
00:56:27,440 --> 00:56:29,317
And the cats meow

821
00:56:30,860 --> 00:56:33,321
I will take you there

822
00:56:34,280 --> 00:56:37,200
I will show you how

823
00:56:54,216 --> 00:56:57,011
And, oh, how they danced,

824
00:56:57,178 --> 00:57:00,681
the little children of Stonehenge,

825
00:57:00,848 --> 00:57:04,977
beneath the haunted moon,

826
00:57:05,144 --> 00:57:08,439
for fear that daybreak

827
00:57:08,606 --> 00:57:11,650
might come too soon.

828
00:57:33,672 --> 00:57:37,885
The problem wasn't that the band was
down. The problem may have been

829
00:57:38,051 --> 00:57:43,807
that there was a Stonehenge monument
in danger of being crushed... by a dwarf.

830
00:57:43,974 --> 00:57:48,312
All right? That tended to understate
the hugeness of the object.

831
00:57:48,478 --> 00:57:52,983
- You're making too big a thing out of it.
- Making a big thing was the idea.

832
00:57:53,150 --> 00:57:55,819
Nigel gave me a drawing
that said 18 inches.

833
00:57:55,986 --> 00:57:56,945
I know...

834
00:57:57,112 --> 00:58:01,241
Whether he knows the difference between
feet and inches is not my problem.

835
00:58:01,408 --> 00:58:05,954
But you're not as confused as him. It's not
your job to be as confused as Nigel is.

836
00:58:06,121 --> 00:58:10,542
It's my job to do what I'm asked to do
by the creative element of this band.

837
00:58:10,709 --> 00:58:13,670
- The audience were laughing.
- So it became a comedy number.

838
00:58:13,837 --> 00:58:18,133
Yes, it fuckin' did, and it was not pleasant
to be part of the comedy onstage.

839
00:58:18,300 --> 00:58:20,719
Backstage, perhaps it was very amusing.

840
00:58:20,886 --> 00:58:24,806
Maybe we just fix the choreography,
keep the dwarf clear.

841
00:58:24,973 --> 00:58:27,392
- What do you mean?
- So he won't trod upon it.

842
00:58:27,559 --> 00:58:31,187
That's not the issue.
I think it's symptomatic of taking on more

843
00:58:31,354 --> 00:58:35,066
than you can, er... er... handle.

844
00:58:35,233 --> 00:58:38,111
It's not the first time
you've messed things up, is it?

845
00:58:38,278 --> 00:58:43,158
There have been some gaping holes
in the business end...

846
00:58:43,324 --> 00:58:47,787
Excuse me. This is a band meeting, right?
Are you here for some reason?

847
00:58:47,954 --> 00:58:51,416
- She's with me.
- Is she now in the band?

848
00:58:51,583 --> 00:58:53,751
I care what happens to the band.

849
00:58:53,918 --> 00:58:58,381
David, whenever a single ruffle comes
into this adolescent fantasy world

850
00:58:58,548 --> 00:59:00,884
you guys have built around yourself,

851
00:59:01,050 --> 00:59:04,137
you start screaming like a bunch
of poncey hairdressers!

852
00:59:04,304 --> 00:59:07,682
It's just a problem! It gets solved!

853
00:59:07,849 --> 00:59:13,104
It doesn't! If it got solved, that would be
all right, but it doesn't get solved.

854
00:59:13,271 --> 00:59:15,982
I mean, what got solved tonight?

855
00:59:16,149 --> 00:59:20,528
For one single thing that goes wrong,
a hundred things go right.

856
00:59:20,695 --> 00:59:22,822
Do you know what
I spend my time doing?

857
00:59:22,989 --> 00:59:26,909
I sleep two or three hours a night.
There's no sex and drugs for Ian, David.

858
00:59:27,076 --> 00:59:29,078
You know what I do?
I find lost luggage.

859
00:59:29,245 --> 00:59:31,914
I locate mandolin strings
in the middle of Austin.

860
00:59:32,081 --> 00:59:34,333
I prise the rent out of the local Hebrews.

861
00:59:34,500 --> 00:59:37,378
Get someone else to find luggage,

862
00:59:37,545 --> 00:59:40,131
and you concentrate on the stage.

863
00:59:40,298 --> 00:59:44,677
- You'd like me to be road manager?
- No! All bad blood aside...

864
00:59:44,844 --> 00:59:48,472
What Dave is trying to say,
if you'd let him get a word through,

865
00:59:48,639 --> 00:59:53,728
- Is you could maybe do with some help.
- Some help?

866
00:59:53,894 --> 00:59:56,480
- Managing the band.
- It's very simple.

867
00:59:56,647 --> 01:00:00,401
Maybe there's someone already here...
We don't have to pay insurance.

868
01:00:00,568 --> 01:00:04,697
We don't have to pay extra room...
since she's already here, among us,

869
01:00:04,864 --> 01:00:08,951
- And she's capable of taking over.
- "She"? Wait a minute.

870
01:00:09,118 --> 01:00:11,328
Who do you think I'm talking about?

871
01:00:11,495 --> 01:00:14,665
I would never have dreamed
it was her you were talking about.

872
01:00:14,915 --> 01:00:17,501
I am offering to help out here.

873
01:00:17,668 --> 01:00:20,254
You're offering to co-manage
the band with me.

874
01:00:20,421 --> 01:00:22,923
Yes, that is exactly it.

875
01:00:23,090 --> 01:00:27,303
I'm not gonna co-manage with some girl
just cos she's your girlfriend!

876
01:00:27,469 --> 01:00:32,057
Oh! "Girlfriend", is it? I don't know
what you're doing managing the band!

877
01:00:32,224 --> 01:00:34,768
- Why don't we just...
- Shut up!

878
01:00:34,935 --> 01:00:39,022
This is my position. I am not managing it
with you or any other woman.

879
01:00:39,189 --> 01:00:43,068
Especially one who dresses like an
Australian's nightmare. So fuck you!

880
01:00:43,235 --> 01:00:47,656
Fuck all of you! Because I quit, all right?
That's it. Good night.

881
01:00:57,541 --> 01:01:01,128
Can I raise a practical question
at this point?

882
01:01:01,295 --> 01:01:03,422
Are we gonna do Stonehenge tomorrow?

883
01:01:03,588 --> 01:01:06,758
No, we're not gonna
fuckin' do Stonehenge!

884
01:01:06,925 --> 01:01:09,428
OK, we're all set. Thank you.

885
01:01:09,845 --> 01:01:15,684
All right, fellas. I got the tickets. We're on
the 3.10 flight at gate 24, all right?

886
01:01:15,851 --> 01:01:20,605
It arrives at 4 o'clock in Colorado. Then
we got a limo to take us to the Lodge.

887
01:01:20,772 --> 01:01:23,567
It's about 100 yards
from Rainbow Trout Studio.

888
01:01:23,733 --> 01:01:28,405
What I've done is to arrange
a whole load of charts.

889
01:01:28,572 --> 01:01:33,326
- This is so great.
- We know that the band's sign is Virgo.

890
01:01:33,493 --> 01:01:38,331
You see, Saturn's in the third house,
and it's a bit rocky.

891
01:01:38,498 --> 01:01:44,379
But because Virgo is one of the most
highly intelligent signs of the zodiac,

892
01:01:44,546 --> 01:01:47,465
we're gonna pull through this
with great aplomb.

893
01:01:47,632 --> 01:01:49,134
Has someone not got one?

894
01:01:49,300 --> 01:01:54,389
Nigel hasn't got one.
Nigel! Nigel! We got pages for you here.

895
01:01:55,265 --> 01:01:57,267
He's got one. He's got it.

896
01:01:57,434 --> 01:02:00,728
Think what a jumble
a tour book usually is...

897
01:02:00,895 --> 01:02:02,897
- He's got one.
- Right.

898
01:02:03,064 --> 01:02:06,568
What I want to explain to you
is that Denver...

899
01:02:07,277 --> 01:02:11,364
How would you characterise your
relationship with David over the years?

900
01:02:11,531 --> 01:02:14,075
- Has it changed in any way?
- Not really.

901
01:02:14,242 --> 01:02:19,664
I mean, you know, we've grown up...
but really it's not...

902
01:02:19,831 --> 01:02:24,127
No, not really.
We feel like children much of the time,

903
01:02:24,293 --> 01:02:26,546
even when we're playing.

904
01:02:26,713 --> 01:02:29,132
We're closer than brothers.

905
01:02:29,799 --> 01:02:31,801
Brothers always fight.

906
01:02:31,968 --> 01:02:35,096
Sort of... disagreements and all that.

907
01:02:35,263 --> 01:02:39,267
We really have a relationship that's way,
way past that.

908
01:02:45,523 --> 01:02:48,776
- He can't play any more.
- You know the parts.

909
01:02:48,943 --> 01:02:51,946
If he knew the fuckin' part,
he'd play it, wouldn't he?

910
01:02:52,113 --> 01:02:56,867
- Are you walking out? Great!
- Just tell me what we're supposed to do.

911
01:02:57,034 --> 01:02:59,537
We're supposed to play the fuckin' thing!

912
01:02:59,704 --> 01:03:02,498
- We've spent an hour and a half...
- I'm doing my part!

913
01:03:02,665 --> 01:03:06,377
You know what would make this a lot
simpler? I hate to cut right to it here.

914
01:03:06,544 --> 01:03:11,215
Why don't you play this alone, without
some angel hanging over your head?

915
01:03:11,382 --> 01:03:14,301
Jesus Christ!
This is fuckin' all we need.

916
01:03:14,468 --> 01:03:18,055
You can't fuckin' concentrate
because of your fuckin' wife!

917
01:03:18,222 --> 01:03:20,516
- It's your fuckin' wife!
- She's not my wife.

918
01:03:20,683 --> 01:03:24,687
Whatever the fuck she is,
we can't fuckin' do the track!

919
01:03:24,853 --> 01:03:28,524
- This is unbelievable!
- No, it's not unbelievable at all!

920
01:03:28,691 --> 01:03:32,820
Am I losing my fuckin' mind?!
Could you check me on this?

921
01:03:32,987 --> 01:03:35,656
I don't understand
what this has to do with anything!

922
01:03:35,823 --> 01:03:40,786
We're very lucky, in a sense,
that we've got two visionaries in the band.

923
01:03:40,953 --> 01:03:43,622
David and Nigel are both like...

924
01:03:44,540 --> 01:03:47,501
Like poets,
like Shelley or Byron or people like that.

925
01:03:48,001 --> 01:03:50,963
They're two totally distinct
types of visionaries.

